  "prompt": "Why sound waves cannot be polarized?",
  "response": "Sound waves cannot be polarized, because they are **longitudinal** waves.\n\nHere's why that's important:\n\n*   **Polarization:** Polarization is a property that applies to transverse waves.  It refers to the direction of the oscillation (vibration) relative to the direction the wave is traveling.  A wave is polarized if its oscillations are confined to a single plane.\n\n*   **Transverse Waves:** In transverse waves (like light or waves on a string), the oscillations are *perpendicular* to the direction of wave propagation.  Because the oscillations are perpendicular, there's a \"direction\" to the oscillation that can be aligned or filtered.\n\n*   **Longitudinal Waves:** In longitudinal waves (like sound in air), the oscillations are *parallel* to the direction of wave propagation.  The wave travels as compressions and rarefactions (regions of high and low density/pressure) along the direction of travel.  Since the motion is along the same line as the wave's travel, there is no \"direction\" *perpendicular* to the propagation that can be filtered or aligned. There's no sideways vibration to align in a particular direction.\n\n**In summary:** Polarization relies on having oscillations perpendicular to the wave's direction of travel. Sound waves, being longitudinal, lack this perpendicular oscillation and therefore cannot be polarized.",
